\f1 death of Dmitri Mendeleev (1834-1907), 
\f2\fs28 \cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Russian {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemistry"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 chemist}} and inventor. He is best remembered for formulating the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periodic_Law"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Periodic Law}} and creating a farsighted version of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periodic_table"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 periodic table of elements}}. He used the Periodic Law not only to correct the then-accepted properties of some known elements, such as the valence and atomic weight of uranium, but also to predict the properties of eight elements that were yet to be discovered.
